<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="772" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6887946" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6887946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6887946/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="772" startId="169.[2064,2236,1166,1200]" targetBox="[1450,2040,981,1394]" targetPageId="169">
<paragraph blockId="169.[2064,2659,969,1397]" pageId="169" pageNumber="772">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2064,2240,1166,1200]" pageId="169" pageNumber="772">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from three of the Ssese Is (Bugala, Bunyama, Kome) in NW part of Lake Victoria, Uganda, and extreme mainland SW Kenya (Nyabera Marsh).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="772" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="169.[2064,2659,969,1397]" lastBlockId="169.[1450,2657,1411,1948]" pageId="169" pageNumber="772">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2064,2342,1363,1397]" pageId="169" pageNumber="772">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 132-149 mm, tail 148-156 mm, ear 15-16 mm, hindfoot 31-32 mm; weight 60-83 g. The Lake Victoria Groove-toothed Swamp Rat is a medium-sized rodent with grooved upper incisors. Fur is warm tawny buff slightly speckled with black above, brownish gray below, and yellowish gray on flanks. Very distinct black mid-dorsalstripe extends from forehead to base oftail. Nose, base of ears, and area around eyes and at base of ears may be rufous. Margins of ears are covered with black hairs. Soles of feet pale (not blackish). Tail is long (c.113% of head-body length), bicolored, blackish above and yellowish below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
